me in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Verdun","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: habitational name from any of several places in France called Verdun. The placename is probably of Gaulish origin, deriving from <i>ver(n)</i> ‘alder’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill, fortress’.","Spanish and Catalan: habitational name from Verdú in Catalonia (Spain), which has the same origin as the French name (see 1 above).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Verdon  , a cognate of 1 above. This surname is very rare in Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Virden","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Verdun  ."]},{"name":"Verdon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Marcel, Pierre, Renaud, Sylvie.","French: habitational name from (Le) Verdon, the name of several places in various parts of France, for example in Dordogne, Gironde, and Marne. Compare   Ferdon  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Verdun, the name of a fief in Vessey (Manche), France. Compare   Verdun  ."]},{"name":"Varden","meanings":["English: variant of   Verdun  ."]}]},{"name":"Bertram","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. Ravens were traditional symbols of wisdom in Germanic mythology; Odin was regularly accompanied by ravens called Hugin and Munin. This name was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain.  See also  Bertrand ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":4,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":24,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":34,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":44,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Bertram de Verdun was born about 1062, his father, Bertram I de Verdun, was 24 and his mother, Maude de Modena, was 14. He had at least 1 son with Rohese de Salford. He died about 1129, in Farnham Royal, Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 69, and was buried in England."},"et":{"Abt 1062–about 1129":"umbes 1062–umbes 1129","1062–1129":"1062–1129","1065–1132":"1065–1132","1066–1129":"1066–1129","1107–1166":"1107–1166","1040–1100":"1040–1100","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","30 November 1107"